<h2>The Sound Alert</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Explain that Timerrapp's timer plays a clear audio alert when time expires. Describe how to test the sound before the exam using the sound test button on the main timer page. Note that volume should be set at the system level beforehand. Mention that the alert fires even if the browser tab is in the background, as long as it's not closed.]</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>Will it work on a Chromebook?</h3>
<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Yes. Timerrapp runs entirely in the Chrome browser, which is the default on Chromebooks. No installation or extensions required. Just navigate to the page.]</p>

<h3>What happens if the internet goes out?</h3>
<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Once the page loads, the timer runs entirely in the browser using JavaScript. An internet outage during the exam will not stop or reset the timer. The countdown continues independently of the network connection.]</p>

<h3>Can students see it on a classroom projector?</h3>
<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Yes. Connect your laptop or desktop to the projector, open the timer, and press F11 (Windows/Chromebook) or use the browser's fullscreen button. The large digital display is designed to be visible from across a room.]</p>

<h3>What if the tab accidentally closes?</h3>
<p>[PLACEHOLDER — If the browser tab is closed, the timer stops. To prevent this, suggest right-clicking the tab and selecting "Pin tab" — pinned tabs are harder to accidentally close and stay available across browser restarts.]</p>

<h2>Timer vs. Alarm: Which to Use for Exams?</h2>

<p>[PLACEHOLDER — Explain the difference in practical terms: use a countdown timer when the exam starts the moment you click Start (variable start time). Use the <a href="/alarm/">alarm clock</a> when the exam must end at a specific wall-clock time regardless of when it started — for example, all students must stop at 10:45 AM. For most classroom exams, the timer is simpler and more reliable.]</p>

